.TH HSH 1 "May 2026" "Holberton School" "Simple Shell Manual"

.SH NAME
.B hsh
\- a simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.RI [ command ]
.RI [ arguments ]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX shell written in C as part of the Holberton School
curriculum. It reads commands from standard input and executes them.
It supports both interactive and non-interactive modes.

In
.B interactive mode,
the shell displays a prompt
.RB ( "$ " )
and waits for the user to type a command.

In
.B non-interactive mode,
commands are read from a pipe or a file without displaying a prompt.

.SH INVOCATION
.TP
.B Interactive mode:
.RS
.nf
$ ./hsh
$ /bin/ls
$ exit
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B Non-interactive mode:
.RS
.nf
echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
.fi
.RE

.SH BUILTINS

.TP
.B exit
Exits the shell. The exit status is the status of the last command executed.
No argument handling is required.

.TP
.B env
Prints all current environment variables, one per line, in the format
.IR NAME=value .

.SH PATH
When a command is entered without a full path, the shell searches for it
in each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable, separated by colons.

If the command contains a
.BR / ,
it is used directly and PATH is not searched.

If the command is not found,
.B fork
is never called, and an error message is printed to standard error.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 127
Command not found.
.TP
.B 1
General error (fork failure or execution error).

.SH EXAMPLES
Execute a command with full path:
.RS
.nf
$ /bin/ls -l
.fi
.RE

Execute a command using PATH:
.RS
.nf
$ ls -la
.fi
.RE

Print environment variables:
.RS
.nf
$ env
.fi
.RE

Exit the shell:
.RS
.nf
$ exit
.fi
.RE

.SH COMPILATION
.nf
gcc -Wall -Werror -Wextra -pedantic -std=gnu89 *.c -o hsh
.fi

